'''''The Neddeaus of Duqesne Island''''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] comedy [[web series]], which premiered on the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]'s CBC Comedy web platform in 2017.<ref name=weirdness>[http://vancouversun.com/entertainment/local-arts/workaholic-vancouver-native-kelly-mccormack-embraces-digital-weirdness "Workaholic Vancouver native Kelly McCormack embraces digital weirdness"]. ''[[Vancouver Sun]]'', July 25, 2017.</ref>
A [[mockumentary]] presented as "lost footage" of a 1970s-era documentary, the series focuses on the Neddeaus, a family who have lived in isolation on a remote [[Northern Ontario]] island and are being profiled in a documentary by filmmaker Ford Francis Mayflower. Its premiere was accompanied by ''Not for Broadcast'', a short promotional trailer which explored the series' fictionalized backstory as a documentary film which was made in the 1970s, but suppressed by the CBC for political reasons and never seen by anyone outside of Canada's media and political elites until 2017; the trailer included commentary from public figures such as [[Jean Chrétien]] and [[David Suzuki]].<ref>[https://occhimagazine.com/actress-kelly-mccormack-talks-the-neddeaus-of-duqesne-island-and-syfys-killjoys/ "Actress Kelly McCormack Talks “The Neddeaus of Duqesne Island” and SyFy’s “Killjoys”"]. ''Occhimag'', July 13, 2017.</ref>
Its cast includes Tara Samuel, [[Colin Mochrie]], Tim Walker, [[Kelly McCormack]], Aaron Schroeder, Ted Martin, Keith Stanton, Caitlin Driscoll and [[Cara Gee]]. Schroeder was the writer and creator of the series, and Schroeder and McCormack were the executive producers.<ref name=weirdness/>
The series was produced by Floyder Films and Duqesne Island Productions.<ref>[http://playbackonline.ca/2017/05/25/cbc-goes-for-the-x-factor-with-ott-service/ "CBC reveals plans for new OTT service"]. ''[[Playback (website)|Playback]]'', May 25, 2017.</ref>
The series received three [[Canadian Screen Award]] nominations at the [[6th Canadian Screen Awards]] in 2018, for Best Direction in a Web Program or Series (Sam Zvibleman), Best Actor in a Web Program or Series (Schroeder) and Best Actress in a Web Program or Series (Samuel). Zvibleman won the award for Best Direction.
